## Session 36b Summary: Deep Focus on Kt Complexity of delta(n)

### What was accomplished

**8 new experiments** extending Session 20's analysis of `Kt(delta(n)|n)`:

| Experiment | Key Result |
|---|---|
| PACF analysis | AR(7) optimal (BIC). PACF drops to 0.056 at lag 2. Short direct memory. |
| Multi-compression | bz2 (36.5%) > lzma (43%) > gzip (56%). diff(delta) even better. |
| Compression scaling | Converges to ~5.8 bits/value by N=10K. Entropy rate is **finite**. |
| Kt(1..N) growth | Kt ~ 5.58\*N. Information is **EXTENSIVE** (linear in N). |
| Block MI | MI ~ 0.55\*log(L). Long-range correlations confirmed. |
| DFA/Hurst | H = 1.31. Crossover at scale 572. Two-regime structure. |
| Transfer entropy | TE(n→delta) = 0.013 << TE(delta→delta) = 0.051. n is **useless**. |
| Spectral structure | 1/f^1.70 continuum. **No** discrete lines, algebraic relations, or sparsifiability. RMSE < 1 needs 82% of modes. |

### Key conclusion

**The R^{-1}(n) + delta(n) decomposition is definitively a dead end for polylog algorithms.** The 1/f spectrum has no exploitable algebraic structure (answering Session 20's open question). All information about delta is sequential, not computable from n.

